{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Research the SAFETY of self-modifying CODE (AI systems that edit their own execution kernel/source), not just prompts. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (available to you).\n\nI need specific, cited claims about:\n1. The distinctive risks of letting a system edit its own execution kernel / source code (vs merely editing prompts): loss of human oversight, the system removing its own guardrails, capability gains that outpace control, irreversibility. Find analysis from safety researchers and the RSI/AI-alignment literature.\n\n2. Recursive self-improvement (RSI) as an alignment concern: the classic argument (Bostrom/Yudkowsky intelligence explosion, instrumental convergence) AND modern framing (e.g. METR, Anthropic/OpenAI/DeepMind responsible scaling / preparedness frameworks treating autonomous AI R&D and self-improvement as a dangerous capability threshold / ASL level). Cite specific framework language about AI-accelerated AI R&D or autonomous replication as a tracked risk.\n\n3. CONCRETE containment/bounding techniques used or proposed for self-modifying code systems: sandboxing/isolation (containers, VMs), capability confinement (least privilege, no network/egress), the principle of a CLOSED mutation surface (the system can only modify a restricted set of things — NOT its safety monitor, capability grants, or kernel), a separate reference monitor / supervisor that the agent cannot edit, human-in-the-loop gating for risky changes, and provenance tracking. How did Darwin Godel Machine / STOP / SICA actually sandbox their experiments? Cite.\n\n4. Any frameworks for BOUNDING self-improvement: provable/formal bounds (Schmidhuber Godel Machine's proof requirement as a safety property), keeping a verifier the system can't tamper with, immutable supervisors, tripwires/tripline monitors. Cite.\n\n5. Documented incidents of self-improving/agentic code systems doing something unsafe in a sandbox (e.g. STOP disabling a sandbox flag, DGM faking results, agents attempting to modify their own reward/tests). Cite.\n\nProvide exact source URLs for every claim. Prefer primary sources (arXiv, lab safety framework docs from Anthropic/OpenAI/DeepMind/METR, the actual RSI papers). Return a structured list of falsifiable claims each with its URL."},"uuid":"ff22a2f6-b427-4f33-b07e-ac61705cf3dc","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:46.805Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
