{"parentUuid":"d19284d1-ff92-4170-a56f-d4664cce671e","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01RKx1ewbk13dyGSPjyYCtk6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_011FwjB8uCZh8gDk8HWCWAEU","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"METR autonomy autonomous replication AI R&D dangerous capability evaluation"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1108,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2298,"cache_read_input_tokens":11944,"output_tokens":252,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2298},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1108,"output_tokens":252,"cache_read_input_tokens":11944,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2298,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2298,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG25TQErp5gXjen1P4fd","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"db63ff82-2d78-4a51-94e6-add703c5d9cb","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:09.301Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"fb2f8c02-9397-4961-ae95-a42c5fee2cbb","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BGmtixekHhmAwM5CN5iW56","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Anthropic Responsible Scaling Policy AI R&D autonomous capability threshold ASL self-improvement\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy \\\\ Anthropic\",\"url\":\"https://www.anthropic.com/news/anthropics-responsible-scaling-policy\"},{\"title\":\"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy (version 3.0)\",\"url\":\"https://anthropic.com/responsible-scaling-policy/rsp-v3-0\"},{\"title\":\"Anthropic Responsible Scaling Policy – ETO AGORA\",\"url\":\"https://agora.eto.tech/instrument/768\"},{\"title\":\"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy (version 2.2)\",\"url\":\"https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/872c653b2d0501d6ab44cf87f43e1dc4853e4d37.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy Version 1.0 Effective September 19, 2023\",\"url\":\"https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/1adf000c8f675958c2ee23805d91aaade1cd4613/responsible-scaling-policy.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Anthropic details Responsible Scaling Policy for frontier AI\",\"url\":\"https://digital.nemko.com/news/anthropic-ai-safety-strategy-what-enterprises-must-know\"},{\"title\":\"Anthropic’s Transparency Hub \\\\ Anthropic\",\"url\":\"https://www.anthropic.com/transparency\"},{\"title\":\"Responsible Scaling Policy Updates \\\\ Anthropic\",\"url\":\"https://www.anthropic.com/responsible-scaling-policy\"}]\n\nI've found comprehensive information about Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy (RSP). Here's what the search reveals:\n\n## Overview\n\nAnthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy is a series of technical and organizational protocols adopted to help manage the risks of developing increasingly capable AI systems. The RSP focuses on catastrophic risks – those where an AI model directly causes large scale devastation.\n\n## AI Safety Levels (ASL) Framework\n\nThe RSP defines a framework called AI Safety Levels (ASL) for addressing catastrophic risks, modeled loosely after the US government's biosafety level (BSL) standards for handling of dangerous biological materials. The approach introduces AI Safety Levels (ASL) that scale safeguards with capability, sets clear thresholds when tighter controls are required, and emphasizes rigorous pre-deployment testing, security hardening, and operational oversight before releasing higher-risk systems.\n\n## Autonomous AI R&D Capability Threshold\n\nThe Autonomous AI Research and Development (AI R&D) Capability Threshold is the ability to either fully automate the work of an entry-level remote-only Researcher at Anthropic, or cause dramatic acceleration in the rate of effective scaling. This capability could greatly increase the pace of AI development, potentially leading to rapid and unpredictable advances in AI capabilities and associated risks.\n\n## Self-Improvement and Model Development\n\nThe policy includes a checkpoint for autonomous AI capabilities that will prompt additional evaluation of the model's capabilities and accelerate preparation of stronger safeguards, rather than triggering higher safety standards automatically.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"09e49419-9064-466a-b0f0-ed4f3ec5cbed","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:18.545Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Anthropic Responsible Scaling Policy AI R&D autonomous capability threshold ASL self-improvement","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01UbpZD1gh2dXPbovzjrY46Q","content":[{"title":"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy \\ Anthropic","url":"https://www.anthropic.com/news/anthropics-responsible-scaling-policy"},{"title":"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy (version 3.0)","url":"https://anthropic.com/responsible-scaling-policy/rsp-v3-0"},{"title":"Anthropic Responsible Scaling Policy – ETO AGORA","url":"https://agora.eto.tech/instrument/768"},{"title":"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy (version 2.2)","url":"https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/872c653b2d0501d6ab44cf87f43e1dc4853e4d37.pdf"},{"title":"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy Version 1.0 Effective September 19, 2023","url":"https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/1adf000c8f675958c2ee23805d91aaade1cd4613/responsible-scaling-policy.pdf"},{"title":"Anthropic details Responsible Scaling Policy for frontier AI","url":"https://digital.nemko.com/news/anthropic-ai-safety-strategy-what-enterprises-must-know"},{"title":"Anthropic’s Transparency Hub \\ Anthropic","url":"https://www.anthropic.com/transparency"},{"title":"Responsible Scaling Policy Updates \\ Anthropic","url":"https://www.anthropic.com/responsible-scaling-policy"}]},"I've found comprehensive information about Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy (RSP). Here's what the search reveals:\n\n## Overview\n\nAnthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy is a series of technical and organizational protocols adopted to help manage the risks of developing increasingly capable AI systems. The RSP focuses on catastrophic risks – those where an AI model directly causes large scale devastation.\n\n## AI Safety Levels (ASL) Framework\n\nThe RSP defines a framework called AI Safety Levels (ASL) for addressing catastrophic risks, modeled loosely after the US government's biosafety level (BSL) standards for handling of dangerous biological materials. The approach introduces AI Safety Levels (ASL) that scale safeguards with capability, sets clear thresholds when tighter controls are required, and emphasizes rigorous pre-deployment testing, security hardening, and operational oversight before releasing higher-risk systems.\n\n## Autonomous AI R&D Capability Threshold\n\nThe Autonomous AI Research and Development (AI R&D) Capability Threshold is the ability to either fully automate the work of an entry-level remote-only Researcher at Anthropic, or cause dramatic acceleration in the rate of effective scaling. This capability could greatly increase the pace of AI development, potentially leading to rapid and unpredictable advances in AI capabilities and associated risks.\n\n## Self-Improvement and Model Development\n\nThe policy includes a checkpoint for autonomous AI capabilities that will prompt additional evaluation of the model's capabilities and accelerate preparation of stronger safeguards, rather than triggering higher safety standards automatically."],"durationSeconds":9.518328167000785,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"fb2f8c02-9397-4961-ae95-a42c5fee2cbb","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"db63ff82-2d78-4a51-94e6-add703c5d9cb","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011FwjB8uCZh8gDk8HWCWAEU","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"METR autonomy autonomous replication AI R&D dangerous capability evaluation\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"METR | AI Wiki\",\"url\":\"https://aiwiki.ai/wiki/metr\"},{\"title\":\"Research - METR\",\"url\":\"https://metr.org/research/\"},{\"title\":\"The AI Risk Spectrum: From Dangerous Capabilities to Existential Threats\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.13700\"},{\"title\":\"Evaluation Reports - METR\",\"url\":\"https://metr.org/evaluations/\"},{\"title\":\"Common Elements of Frontier AI Safety Policies - METR\",\"url\":\"https://metr.org/common-elements\"},{\"title\":\"OpenAI GPT-5 System Card\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.03267\"},{\"title\":\"Evaluating frontier AI R&D capabilities of language model agents against human experts - METR\",\"url\":\"https://metr.org/blog/2024-11-22-evaluating-r-d-capabilities-of-llms/\"},{\"title\":\"Resources | METR’s Autonomy Evaluation Resources\",\"url\":\"https://evaluations.metr.org/\"},{\"title\":\"Example Protocol | METR’s Autonomy Evaluation Resources\",\"url\":\"https://evaluations.metr.org/example-protocol/\"},{\"title\":\"METR\",\"url\":\"https://metr.org/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about METR's work on autonomy, autonomous replication, AI R&D, and dangerous capability evaluation:\n\n## Overview\n\nMETR's collection of resources is designed for evaluating potentially dangerous autonomous capabilities of frontier models. METR's AI evaluations research focuses on assessing broad autonomous capabilities and the ability of AI systems to accelerate AI R&D.\n\n## Key Focus Areas\n\nMETR has historically focused on a specific cluster of catastrophic risk scenarios including autonomous replication, AI R&D acceleration, and cyberattacks. At least four threat models of concern are identified as AI systems become more capable: Cyberoffense, AI R&D, Autonomous Replication and Adaptation (ARA), and potentially Biological Weapons Assistance.\n\n## Autonomous Replication\n\nAutonomous replication represents the ability of AI systems to independently create copies of themselves, spread across computing infrastructure, and adapt to obstacles without human assistance, combining making money to fund operations, acquiring new computing resources, installing and maintaining copies of itself on new systems, and adapting to changing circumstances or security measures.\n\n## Current Evaluations\n\nMETR's evaluations assess a model's performance on its 77-task autonomous capability suite, with results expressed as the fraction of tasks completed successfully and the estimated 50%-task-completion time horizon. METR, a research nonprofit that works on assessing whether frontier AI systems could pose catastrophic risks to society, has conducted external evaluations of systems like GPT-5 for risks from autonomy.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9223c92c-1322-4bb0-87ef-3d61b7bc2aa6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:19.092Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"METR autonomy autonomous replication AI R&D dangerous capability evaluation","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_012JejKLMnsYh8RjB5Xw4q82","content":[{"title":"METR | AI Wiki","url":"https://aiwiki.ai/wiki/metr"},{"title":"Research - METR","url":"https://metr.org/research/"},{"title":"The AI Risk Spectrum: From Dangerous Capabilities to Existential Threats","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.13700"},{"title":"Evaluation Reports - METR","url":"https://metr.org/evaluations/"},{"title":"Common Elements of Frontier AI Safety Policies - METR","url":"https://metr.org/common-elements"},{"title":"OpenAI GPT-5 System Card","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.03267"},{"title":"Evaluating frontier AI R&D capabilities of language model agents against human experts - METR","url":"https://metr.org/blog/2024-11-22-evaluating-r-d-capabilities-of-llms/"},{"title":"Resources | METR’s Autonomy Evaluation Resources","url":"https://evaluations.metr.org/"},{"title":"Example Protocol | METR’s Autonomy Evaluation Resources","url":"https://evaluations.metr.org/example-protocol/"},{"title":"METR","url":"https://metr.org/"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about METR's work on autonomy, autonomous replication, AI R&D, and dangerous capability evaluation:\n\n## Overview\n\nMETR's collection of resources is designed for evaluating potentially dangerous autonomous capabilities of frontier models. METR's AI evaluations research focuses on assessing broad autonomous capabilities and the ability of AI systems to accelerate AI R&D.\n\n## Key Focus Areas\n\nMETR has historically focused on a specific cluster of catastrophic risk scenarios including autonomous replication, AI R&D acceleration, and cyberattacks. At least four threat models of concern are identified as AI systems become more capable: Cyberoffense, AI R&D, Autonomous Replication and Adaptation (ARA), and potentially Biological Weapons Assistance.\n\n## Autonomous Replication\n\nAutonomous replication represents the ability of AI systems to independently create copies of themselves, spread across computing infrastructure, and adapt to obstacles without human assistance, combining making money to fund operations, acquiring new computing resources, installing and maintaining copies of itself on new systems, and adapting to changing circumstances or security measures.\n\n## Current Evaluations\n\nMETR's evaluations assess a model's performance on its 77-task autonomous capability suite, with results expressed as the fraction of tasks completed successfully and the estimated 50%-task-completion time horizon. METR, a research nonprofit that works on assessing whether frontier AI systems could pose catastrophic risks to society, has conducted external evaluations of systems like GPT-5 for risks from autonomy."],"durationSeconds":9.608650667000562,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"db63ff82-2d78-4a51-94e6-add703c5d9cb","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"d19284d1-ff92-4170-a56f-d4664cce671e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CYTkSF2fA7TWaJgyKDYdky","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"OpenAI Preparedness Framework self-improvement autonomous AI R&D critical risk category\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Why OpenAI needs to \\\"gain confidence in the safety of running systems that can self-improve\\\"\",\"url\":\"https://www.prinzai.com/p/why-openai-needs-to-gain-confidence\"},{\"title\":\"OpenAI framework: AI now 'on the cusp of doing new science'\",\"url\":\"https://www.rdworldonline.com/openai-framework-ai-now-on-the-cusp-of-doing-new-science/\"},{\"title\":\"Our updated Preparedness Framework | OpenAI\",\"url\":\"https://openai.com/index/updating-our-preparedness-framework/\"},{\"title\":\"OpenAI Preparedness Framework 2.0 - by Zvi Mowshowitz\",\"url\":\"https://thezvi.substack.com/p/openai-preparedness-framework-20\"},{\"title\":\"We read every labs safety plan so you don't have to: 2025 edition — EA Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/fHWtYTyahQoSsfzke/we-read-every-labs-safety-plan-so-you-don-t-have-to-2025\"},{\"title\":\"OpenAI Preparedness Framework 2025: What It Actually Guarantees About AI Safety\",\"url\":\"https://www.libertify.com/interactive-library/openai-preparedness-framework-2025-safety-analysis/\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) The 2025 OpenAI Preparedness Framework does not guarantee any AI risk mitigation practices: a proof-of-concept for affordance analyses of AI safety policies\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395968831_The_2025_OpenAI_Preparedness_Framework_does_not_guarantee_any_AI_risk_mitigation_practices_a_proof-of-concept_for_affordance_analyses_of_AI_safety_policies\"},{\"title\":\"Large language model-powered AI systems achieve self-replication with no   human intervention\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.17378\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about OpenAI's Preparedness Framework regarding self-improvement, autonomous AI R&D, and critical risk categories:\n\n## AI Self-Improvement and Autonomous R&D\n\nOpenAI's Preparedness Framework addresses the potential for AI to become \"recursively self improving,\" warning that the resulting \"major acceleration in the rate of AI R&D\" could rapidly introduce new capabilities and risks. This acceleration could outpace current safety measures, rendering oversight \"insufficient\" and explicitly flagging the danger of losing \"maintaining human control\" over the AI system itself.\n\n## Critical Risk Category\n\nOpenAI streamlined risk levels to two clear thresholds: High capability, which could amplify existing pathways to severe harm, and Critical capability, which could introduce unprecedented new pathways to severe harm. Systems that reach Critical capability also require safeguards that sufficiently minimize associated risks during development.\n\nThe \"Critical\" risk category relates to a model that is capable of recursively self improving (i.e., fully automated AI R&D), defined as either a superhuman research scientist agent or causing a generational model improvement in 1/5th the wall-clock time of equivalent progress in 2024.\n\n## Key Focus Areas\n\nCurrent focus areas include Long-range Autonomy, Sandbagging, Autonomous Replication and Adaptation, Undermining Safeguards, and Nuclear and Radiological.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"2e09a964-30ce-4f13-9ad7-05916b3b3ec6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:19.794Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"OpenAI Preparedness Framework self-improvement autonomous AI R&D critical risk category","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_017LdpCJj2wV6Fpwqi2N54ci","content":[{"title":"Why OpenAI needs to \"gain confidence in the safety of running systems that can self-improve\"","url":"https://www.prinzai.com/p/why-openai-needs-to-gain-confidence"},{"title":"OpenAI framework: AI now 'on the cusp of doing new science'","url":"https://www.rdworldonline.com/openai-framework-ai-now-on-the-cusp-of-doing-new-science/"},{"title":"Our updated Preparedness Framework | OpenAI","url":"https://openai.com/index/updating-our-preparedness-framework/"},{"title":"OpenAI Preparedness Framework 2.0 - by Zvi Mowshowitz","url":"https://thezvi.substack.com/p/openai-preparedness-framework-20"},{"title":"We read every labs safety plan so you don't have to: 2025 edition — EA Forum","url":"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/fHWtYTyahQoSsfzke/we-read-every-labs-safety-plan-so-you-don-t-have-to-2025"},{"title":"OpenAI Preparedness Framework 2025: What It Actually Guarantees About AI Safety","url":"https://www.libertify.com/interactive-library/openai-preparedness-framework-2025-safety-analysis/"},{"title":"(PDF) The 2025 OpenAI Preparedness Framework does not guarantee any AI risk mitigation practices: a proof-of-concept for affordance analyses of AI safety policies","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395968831_The_2025_OpenAI_Preparedness_Framework_does_not_guarantee_any_AI_risk_mitigation_practices_a_proof-of-concept_for_affordance_analyses_of_AI_safety_policies"},{"title":"Large language model-powered AI systems achieve self-replication with no   human intervention","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.17378"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about OpenAI's Preparedness Framework regarding self-improvement, autonomous AI R&D, and critical risk categories:\n\n## AI Self-Improvement and Autonomous R&D\n\nOpenAI's Preparedness Framework addresses the potential for AI to become \"recursively self improving,\" warning that the resulting \"major acceleration in the rate of AI R&D\" could rapidly introduce new capabilities and risks. This acceleration could outpace current safety measures, rendering oversight \"insufficient\" and explicitly flagging the danger of losing \"maintaining human control\" over the AI system itself.\n\n## Critical Risk Category\n\nOpenAI streamlined risk levels to two clear thresholds: High capability, which could amplify existing pathways to severe harm, and Critical capability, which could introduce unprecedented new pathways to severe harm. Systems that reach Critical capability also require safeguards that sufficiently minimize associated risks during development.\n\nThe \"Critical\" risk category relates to a model that is capable of recursively self improving (i.e., fully automated AI R&D), defined as either a superhuman research scientist agent or causing a generational model improvement in 1/5th the wall-clock time of equivalent progress in 2024.\n\n## Key Focus Areas\n\nCurrent focus areas include Long-range Autonomy, Sandbagging, Autonomous Replication and Adaptation, Undermining Safeguards, and Nuclear and Radiological."],"durationSeconds":10.632261207999662,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d19284d1-ff92-4170-a56f-d4664cce671e","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
