{"parentUuid":"02e8d1d1-2b74-4155-891f-9e3348457820","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01LLAPdQ8md5zzooFhPhasWN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Q1iw2tnMzeLLsZPai88chd","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"Schmidhuber Godel Machine proof requirement provably optimal self-rewriting self-referential"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1073,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3824,"cache_read_input_tokens":14242,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3824,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG26bm4Ed8UBqZnwR1fr","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"15686ac8-395b-4eee-905e-a9a5245a769c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:24.953Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"15686ac8-395b-4eee-905e-a9a5245a769c","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Q1iw2tnMzeLLsZPai88chd","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Schmidhuber Godel Machine proof requirement provably optimal self-rewriting self-referential\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[cs/0309048] Goedel Machines: Self-Referential Universal Problem Solvers Making Provably Optimal Self-Improvements\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/cs/0309048\"},{\"title\":\"Gödel Machines: Self-Referential Universal Problem Solvers Making Provably Optimal Self-Improvements TR IDSIA-19-03, Version 2; arXiv:cs.LO/0309048 v2\",\"url\":\"https://people.idsia.ch/~juergen/gmweb2/gmweb2.html\"},{\"title\":\"Gödel Machine - Serious Science\",\"url\":\"https://serious-science.org/godel-machine-10426\"},{\"title\":\"Gödel Machines: Fully Self-referential Optimal Universal Self-improvers\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/225256257_Godel_Machines_Fully_Self-referential_Optimal_Universal_Self-improvers\"},{\"title\":\"Gödel Machines: Fully Self-referential Optimal Universal Self-improvers | Springer Nature Link\",\"url\":\"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-540-68677-4_7\"},{\"title\":\"Jürgen Schmidhuber - Gödel Machines: Fully Self-Referential Optimal Universal Self-improvers · tomrochette.com\",\"url\":\"https://blog.tomrochette.com/agi/papers/jurgen-schmidhuber-godel-machines-fully-self-referential-optimal-universal-self-improvers/\"},{\"title\":\"Gödel Machines: Self-Referential Universal Problem Solvers Making Provably Optimal Self-Improvements TR IDSIA-19-03, Version 4; arXiv:cs.LO/0309048 v4\",\"url\":\"https://people.idsia.ch/~juergen/gmweb4/gmweb4.html\"},{\"title\":\"[PDF] Goedel Machines: Self-Referential Universal Problem Solvers Making Provably Optimal Self-Improvements | Semantic Scholar\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Goedel-Machines:-Self-Referential-Universal-Problem-Schmidhuber/2e45fd58329558b0c9e73cbc1fb9f4f60dbb5ca7\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's information about Schmidhuber's Gödel Machine regarding proof requirements and provably optimal self-rewriting:\n\n## Core Concept\n\nSchmidhuber presents the first class of mathematically rigorous, general, fully self-referential, self-improving, optimally efficient problem solvers. A problem solver rewrites any part of its own code as soon as it has found a proof that the rewrite is useful, where the problem-dependent utility function and the hardware and the entire initial code are described by axioms encoded in an initial proof searcher which is also part of the initial code.\n\n## Proof Requirement\n\nThe searcher systematically and efficiently tests computable proof techniques (programs whose outputs are proofs) until it finds a provably useful, computable self-rewrite. The key requirement is that the first self-change executed by the system will be executed only if it is provably useful in the sense of the present utility function.\n\n## Provably Optimal Property\n\nSuch a self-rewrite is globally optimal—no local maxima—since the code first had to prove that it is not useful to continue the proof search for alternative self-rewrites. This ensures that provably none of all the alternative rewrites and proofs (that could be found in the future by continuing the proof search) is worth waiting for.\n\n## Limitations\n\nEven a Gödel machine with unlimited computational resources must ignore those self-improvements whose effectiveness it cannot prove.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"bd077a35-a203-40a6-8a89-ab6f266f4bfb","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:31.779Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Schmidhuber Godel Machine proof requirement provably optimal self-rewriting self-referential","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01AreE5MxMvxccLS3TfXY8Ph","content":[{"title":"[cs/0309048] Goedel Machines: Self-Referential Universal Problem Solvers Making Provably Optimal Self-Improvements","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/cs/0309048"},{"title":"Gödel Machines: Self-Referential Universal Problem Solvers Making Provably Optimal Self-Improvements TR IDSIA-19-03, Version 2; arXiv:cs.LO/0309048 v2","url":"https://people.idsia.ch/~juergen/gmweb2/gmweb2.html"},{"title":"Gödel Machine - Serious Science","url":"https://serious-science.org/godel-machine-10426"},{"title":"Gödel Machines: Fully Self-referential Optimal Universal Self-improvers","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/225256257_Godel_Machines_Fully_Self-referential_Optimal_Universal_Self-improvers"},{"title":"Gödel Machines: Fully Self-referential Optimal Universal Self-improvers | Springer Nature Link","url":"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-540-68677-4_7"},{"title":"Jürgen Schmidhuber - Gödel Machines: Fully Self-Referential Optimal Universal Self-improvers · tomrochette.com","url":"https://blog.tomrochette.com/agi/papers/jurgen-schmidhuber-godel-machines-fully-self-referential-optimal-universal-self-improvers/"},{"title":"Gödel Machines: Self-Referential Universal Problem Solvers Making Provably Optimal Self-Improvements TR IDSIA-19-03, Version 4; arXiv:cs.LO/0309048 v4","url":"https://people.idsia.ch/~juergen/gmweb4/gmweb4.html"},{"title":"[PDF] Goedel Machines: Self-Referential Universal Problem Solvers Making Provably Optimal Self-Improvements | Semantic Scholar","url":"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Goedel-Machines:-Self-Referential-Universal-Problem-Schmidhuber/2e45fd58329558b0c9e73cbc1fb9f4f60dbb5ca7"}]},"Based on the search results, here's information about Schmidhuber's Gödel Machine regarding proof requirements and provably optimal self-rewriting:\n\n## Core Concept\n\nSchmidhuber presents the first class of mathematically rigorous, general, fully self-referential, self-improving, optimally efficient problem solvers. A problem solver rewrites any part of its own code as soon as it has found a proof that the rewrite is useful, where the problem-dependent utility function and the hardware and the entire initial code are described by axioms encoded in an initial proof searcher which is also part of the initial code.\n\n## Proof Requirement\n\nThe searcher systematically and efficiently tests computable proof techniques (programs whose outputs are proofs) until it finds a provably useful, computable self-rewrite. The key requirement is that the first self-change executed by the system will be executed only if it is provably useful in the sense of the present utility function.\n\n## Provably Optimal Property\n\nSuch a self-rewrite is globally optimal—no local maxima—since the code first had to prove that it is not useful to continue the proof search for alternative self-rewrites. This ensures that provably none of all the alternative rewrites and proofs (that could be found in the future by continuing the proof search) is worth waiting for.\n\n## Limitations\n\nEven a Gödel machine with unlimited computational resources must ignore those self-improvements whose effectiveness it cannot prove."],"durationSeconds":6.597719542000442,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"15686ac8-395b-4eee-905e-a9a5245a769c","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"23c2a198-b311-4356-8359-93d3536c2f14","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SGebE2p1av7hEJyfWUyoSx","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Bostrom Yudkowsky intelligence explosion instrumental convergence recursive self-improvement superintelligence\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Eliezer Yudkowsky - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eliezer_Yudkowsky\"},{\"title\":\"Don't Fear the Reaper: Refuting Bostrom's Superintelligence Argument\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1702.08495\"},{\"title\":\"Superintelligence reference page\",\"url\":\"https://bternarytau.github.io/miscellaneous/superintelligence-reference-page\"},{\"title\":\"Superintelligence - by Nick Bostrom\",\"url\":\"https://fluidself.org/books/science/superintelligence\"},{\"title\":\"Superintelligence 6: Intelligence explosion kinetics — LessWrong\",\"url\":\"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/GT8uvxBjidrmM3MCv/superintelligence-6-intelligence-explosion-kinetics\"},{\"title\":\"1 THE ETHICS OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE (2011) Nick Bostrom Eliezer Yudkowsky\",\"url\":\"https://nickbostrom.com/ethics/artificial-intelligence.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"AGI Safety Literature Review\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1805.01109\"},{\"title\":\"A quick reference guide to Nick Bostrom’s book Superintelligence\",\"url\":\"https://abinitioblog.com/2017/10/22/superintelligence-reference/\"},{\"title\":\"The three main doctrines on the future of AI\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.20050\"},{\"title\":\"Recursive self-improvement - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recursive_self-improvement\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Bostrom, Yudkowsky, and these key concepts in AI safety:\n\n## Intelligence Explosion and Recursive Self-Improvement\n\nRecursively self-improving AI systems quickly transition from subhuman general intelligence to superintelligence in what's known as an intelligence explosion scenario. A successful seed AI could iteratively enhance itself, where an early version of the AI could design an improved version of itself, and the improved version—being smarter than the original—might be able to design an even smarter version of itself, and so forth, potentially resulting in an intelligence explosion.\n\n## Key Figures and Their Contributions\n\nI.J. Good (1965) set forth the classic hypothesis that an AI sufficiently intelligent to understand its own design could redesign itself or create a successor system, more intelligent, which could then redesign itself yet again in a positive feedback cycle, which Good called the \"intelligence explosion\". Yudkowsky's work on the prospect of a runaway intelligence explosion influenced philosopher Nick Bostrom's 2014 book Superintelligence: Paths, Dangers, Strategies.\n\n## Instrumental Convergence\n\nThe instrumental convergence thesis states that there are instrumental goals that will be useful to agents with a wide variety of terminal goals, including self-preservation, resource acquisition, and self-improvement. In response to the instrumental convergence concern, which implies that autonomous decision-making systems with poorly designed goals would have default incentives to mistreat humans, Yudkowsky and other MIRI researchers have recommended work to specify software agents that converge on safe default behaviors.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"3ffa3cd5-2dd8-4aed-b404-468fafc7288b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:32.845Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Bostrom Yudkowsky intelligence explosion instrumental convergence recursive self-improvement superintelligence","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_019aqtAjosKaS1p1UbVRQi1d","content":[{"title":"Eliezer Yudkowsky - Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eliezer_Yudkowsky"},{"title":"Don't Fear the Reaper: Refuting Bostrom's Superintelligence Argument","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1702.08495"},{"title":"Superintelligence reference page","url":"https://bternarytau.github.io/miscellaneous/superintelligence-reference-page"},{"title":"Superintelligence - by Nick Bostrom","url":"https://fluidself.org/books/science/superintelligence"},{"title":"Superintelligence 6: Intelligence explosion kinetics — LessWrong","url":"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/GT8uvxBjidrmM3MCv/superintelligence-6-intelligence-explosion-kinetics"},{"title":"1 THE ETHICS OF ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE (2011) Nick Bostrom Eliezer Yudkowsky","url":"https://nickbostrom.com/ethics/artificial-intelligence.pdf"},{"title":"AGI Safety Literature Review","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1805.01109"},{"title":"A quick reference guide to Nick Bostrom’s book Superintelligence","url":"https://abinitioblog.com/2017/10/22/superintelligence-reference/"},{"title":"The three main doctrines on the future of AI","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.20050"},{"title":"Recursive self-improvement - Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recursive_self-improvement"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about Bostrom, Yudkowsky, and these key concepts in AI safety:\n\n## Intelligence Explosion and Recursive Self-Improvement\n\nRecursively self-improving AI systems quickly transition from subhuman general intelligence to superintelligence in what's known as an intelligence explosion scenario. A successful seed AI could iteratively enhance itself, where an early version of the AI could design an improved version of itself, and the improved version—being smarter than the original—might be able to design an even smarter version of itself, and so forth, potentially resulting in an intelligence explosion.\n\n## Key Figures and Their Contributions\n\nI.J. Good (1965) set forth the classic hypothesis that an AI sufficiently intelligent to understand its own design could redesign itself or create a successor system, more intelligent, which could then redesign itself yet again in a positive feedback cycle, which Good called the \"intelligence explosion\". Yudkowsky's work on the prospect of a runaway intelligence explosion influenced philosopher Nick Bostrom's 2014 book Superintelligence: Paths, Dangers, Strategies.\n\n## Instrumental Convergence\n\nThe instrumental convergence thesis states that there are instrumental goals that will be useful to agents with a wide variety of terminal goals, including self-preservation, resource acquisition, and self-improvement. In response to the instrumental convergence concern, which implies that autonomous decision-making systems with poorly designed goals would have default incentives to mistreat humans, Yudkowsky and other MIRI researchers have recommended work to specify software agents that converge on safe default behaviors."],"durationSeconds":9.052245875000954,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"23c2a198-b311-4356-8359-93d3536c2f14","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"02e8d1d1-2b74-4155-891f-9e3348457820","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01C6Df9qgotmh6u6SK2Mkhk9","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"SICA self-improving coding agent Robeyns sandbox Docker arXiv 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Self-Improving Coding Agent (SICA)\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-improving-coding-agent-sica\"},{\"title\":\"A Self-Improving Coding Agent Maxime Robeyns, University of Bristol\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.15228\"},{\"title\":\"Better Ways to Build Self-Improving AI Agents – Yohei Nakajima\",\"url\":\"https://yoheinakajima.com/better-ways-to-build-self-improving-ai-agents/\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - MaximeRobeyns/self_improving_coding_agent: A coding agent framework, that works on its own codebase. · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/MaximeRobeyns/self_improving_coding_agent\"},{\"title\":\"Paper page - A Self-Improving Coding Agent\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/papers/2504.15228\"},{\"title\":\"Published as a workshop paper at ICLR 2025 SSI-FM A SELF-IMPROVING CODING AGENT\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=rShJCyLsOr\"},{\"title\":\"SWE-EVO: Benchmarking Coding Agents in Long-Horizon Software Evolution Scenarios\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2512.18470v2\"},{\"title\":\"Live-SWE-agent: Can Software Engineering Agents Self-Evolve on the Fly?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.13646\"},{\"title\":\"[2504.15228] A Self-Improving Coding Agent\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.15228\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's information about SICA:\n\n## SICA: Self-Improving Coding Agent\n\nSICA is a self-improving coding agent developed by Maxime Robeyns, Martin Szummer, and Laurence Aitchison (arXiv preprint arXiv:2504.15228, 2025).\n\n### Key Mechanism\n\nSICA enables an agent to directly edit its own agent script: it uses an LLM to propose modifications to its own source code (prompts, heuristics, architecture), applies candidate edits, re-evaluates, and keeps changes that improve metrics.\n\n### Performance Results\n\nThe results demonstrate that self-improvement through an agent system editing its own codebase is possible, particularly in longer-horizon 'agentic' tasks, showing improvements from 17% to 53% on a random subset of SWE Bench Verified, while also achieving a slight decrease in the average time spent per problem.\n\n### Technical Approach\n\nSICA takes the best performing agent from an archive as the meta-agent, which is instructed to look through the archive, identify an improvement, and implement it. The work was published at the ICLR 2025 Workshop on Scaling Self-Improving Foundation Models.\n\nNote: The search results mention sandboxing and agent safety considerations, but don't provide specific details about Docker sandbox implementation in the SICA paper itself.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"6c84d9e2-763c-469b-8c6d-cf0666a83be7","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:33.431Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"SICA self-improving coding agent Robeyns sandbox Docker arXiv 2025","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_011cGgSeRciYyfxCoicxBpMu","content":[{"title":"Self-Improving Coding Agent (SICA)","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/self-improving-coding-agent-sica"},{"title":"A Self-Improving Coding Agent Maxime Robeyns, University of Bristol","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.15228"},{"title":"Better Ways to Build Self-Improving AI Agents – Yohei Nakajima","url":"https://yoheinakajima.com/better-ways-to-build-self-improving-ai-agents/"},{"title":"GitHub - MaximeRobeyns/self_improving_coding_agent: A coding agent framework, that works on its own codebase. · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/MaximeRobeyns/self_improving_coding_agent"},{"title":"Paper page - A Self-Improving Coding Agent","url":"https://huggingface.co/papers/2504.15228"},{"title":"Published as a workshop paper at ICLR 2025 SSI-FM A SELF-IMPROVING CODING AGENT","url":"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=rShJCyLsOr"},{"title":"SWE-EVO: Benchmarking Coding Agents in Long-Horizon Software Evolution Scenarios","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2512.18470v2"},{"title":"Live-SWE-agent: Can Software Engineering Agents Self-Evolve on the Fly?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.13646"},{"title":"[2504.15228] A Self-Improving Coding Agent","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.15228"}]},"Based on the search results, here's information about SICA:\n\n## SICA: Self-Improving Coding Agent\n\nSICA is a self-improving coding agent developed by Maxime Robeyns, Martin Szummer, and Laurence Aitchison (arXiv preprint arXiv:2504.15228, 2025).\n\n### Key Mechanism\n\nSICA enables an agent to directly edit its own agent script: it uses an LLM to propose modifications to its own source code (prompts, heuristics, architecture), applies candidate edits, re-evaluates, and keeps changes that improve metrics.\n\n### Performance Results\n\nThe results demonstrate that self-improvement through an agent system editing its own codebase is possible, particularly in longer-horizon 'agentic' tasks, showing improvements from 17% to 53% on a random subset of SWE Bench Verified, while also achieving a slight decrease in the average time spent per problem.\n\n### Technical Approach\n\nSICA takes the best performing agent from an archive as the meta-agent, which is instructed to look through the archive, identify an improvement, and implement it. The work was published at the ICLR 2025 Workshop on Scaling Self-Improving Foundation Models.\n\nNote: The search results mention sandboxing and agent safety considerations, but don't provide specific details about Docker sandbox implementation in the SICA paper itself."],"durationSeconds":8.623790916999802,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"02e8d1d1-2b74-4155-891f-9e3348457820","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
