{"parentUuid":"b175eca5-7adf-4cbc-922f-f0aca9c66ab7","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"a1cf23d1e97c4e687","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TGv7NRKm2F5jAazzfMkcaY","type":"tool_result","content":"# Autonomous AI R&D Capability Definition\n\nThe webpage does not provide an explicit definition of \"Autonomous AI Research and Development\" as a specific capability threshold.\n\nHowever, regarding autonomy as a tracked dangerous capability, the document states:\n\n**On ASL-3 criteria:** \"ASL-3 refers to systems that substantially increase the risk of catastrophic misuse compared to non-AI baselines (e.g. search engines or textbooks) OR that show low-level autonomous capabilities.\"\n\n**On AI accelerating AI development:** The footnote notes that \"working with frontier AI models is an essential ingredient in developing new methods to mitigate the risk of AI,\" but this describes using models for safety research rather than autonomous self-improvement.\n\n**On ASL-4 safeguards:** The policy indicates that \"ASL-4 measures aren't yet written\" and \"may require methods of assurance that are unsolved research problems today, such as using interpretability methods to demonstrate mechanistically that a model is unlikely to engage in certain catastrophic behaviors.\"\n\nThe document treats autonomy as a concerning capability warranting higher safety levels but does not isolate \"Autonomous AI R&D\" as a distinctly defined threshold separate from broader autonomous capabilities discussions."}]},"uuid":"d8868f0c-7d02-4cba-9c01-215d6e0f8378","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:19.765Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":152519,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Autonomous AI R&D Capability Definition\n\nThe webpage does not provide an explicit definition of \"Autonomous AI Research and Development\" as a specific capability threshold.\n\nHowever, regarding autonomy as a tracked dangerous capability, the document states:\n\n**On ASL-3 criteria:** \"ASL-3 refers to systems that substantially increase the risk of catastrophic misuse compared to non-AI baselines (e.g. search engines or textbooks) OR that show low-level autonomous capabilities.\"\n\n**On AI accelerating AI development:** The footnote notes that \"working with frontier AI models is an essential ingredient in developing new methods to mitigate the risk of AI,\" but this describes using models for safety research rather than autonomous self-improvement.\n\n**On ASL-4 safeguards:** The policy indicates that \"ASL-4 measures aren't yet written\" and \"may require methods of assurance that are unsolved research problems today, such as using interpretability methods to demonstrate mechanistically that a model is unlikely to engage in certain catastrophic behaviors.\"\n\nThe document treats autonomy as a concerning capability warranting higher safety levels but does not isolate \"Autonomous AI R&D\" as a distinctly defined threshold separate from broader autonomous capabilities discussions.","durationMs":10189,"url":"https://www.anthropic.com/news/anthropics-responsible-scaling-policy"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b175eca5-7adf-4cbc-922f-f0aca9c66ab7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
